08721nam a22012135i 9783110540253DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2018963679  a97831105402537 a10.1515/97831105402532doi  a(DE-B1597)479505  a(OCoLC)1102798838  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP291b.C87 2019 4aP291b.C87 2019 7aLAN0090002bisacsh  aET 600qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28006:00aCurrent Approaches to Syntax :bA Comparative Handbook /ced. by András Kertész, Edith Moravcsik, Csilla Rákosi. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (XVI, 600 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Handbooks of Linguistics [CHL] ,x2364-4354 ;v300tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgment -- tContents -- tBiographical Sketches -- t1. Introduction -- tPart I: Approaches to syntax -- t2. Cognitive Grammar -- t3. Construction Grammar -- t4. Simpler Syntax -- t5. Lexical Functional Grammar -- t6. The Decathlon Model -- t7. The Stupendous Success of the Minimalist Program -- t8. The Parallel Architecture -- t9. Usage-based Grammar -- t10. Optimality-theoretic Syntax -- t11. The Functional Discourse Grammar approach to syntax -- t12. Head-Driven Phrase Structure Grammar -- t13. Dependency Grammar -- t14. Combinatory Categorial Grammar -- tPart II: Metatheoretical foundations -- t15. Syntactic knowledge and intersubjectivity -- t16. Hermeneutics and generative linguistics -- t17. The uncertainty of syntactic theorizing -- t18. The multiparadigmatic structure of science and generative grammar -- t19. The philosophy of generative linguistics: best theory criteria -- t20. The research programme of Chomskyan linguistics -- t21. Conclusions: On the use of the comparison of syntactic theories -- tAuthor Index -- tLanguage Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven though the range of phenomena syntactic theories intend to account for is basically the same, the large number of current approaches to syntax shows how differently these phenomena can be interpreted, described, and explained. The goal of the volume is to probe into the question of how exactly these frameworks differ and what if anything they have in common.Descriptions of a sample of current approaches to syntax are presented by their major practitioners (Part I) followed by their metatheoretical underpinnings (Part II). Given that the goal is to facilitate a systematic comparison among the approaches, a checklist of issues was given to the contributors to address. The main headings are Data, Goals, Descriptive Tools, and Criteria for Evaluation. The chapters are structured uniformly allowing an item-by-item survey across the frameworks. The introduction lays out the parameters along which syntactic frameworks must be the same and how they may differ and a final paper draws some conclusions about similarities and differences.The volume is of interest to descriptive linguists, theoreticians of grammar, philosophers of science, and studies of the cognitive science of science.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGenerative grammar. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aSyntactic Theories, Syntactic Metatheories,.1 aAudring, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroccias, Cristiano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaves, Rui P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCulicover, Peter W., econtributor.4ctb